# WTI Regime-Aware Forecasting

**News and Macro Signals for WTI Crude Oil Direction: A Regime-Aware Model for Energy Hedging Decision Support**

Capstone project — Department of Industrial Engineering, Taiwan-Paraguay Polytechnic University (UPTP) & Department of Industrial Management, National Taiwan University of Science and Technology (NTUST)

**Authors:** Filippo Josue Maldonado Centurion, Mathias Nicolas Anastacio Pereira Rodriguez
**Instructor:** Prof. Shih-Hsien Tseng

---

## Overview

Energy-intensive industries (airlines, petrochemicals, logistics) allocate 30–40% of operating costs to fuel, making WTI crude oil direction a critical input for hedging decisions. Existing directional prediction models rely on macro-financial signals published with lags of weeks to months, missing geopolitical shocks that appear in news media days before they show up in price data.

This project develops a **regime-aware XGBoost model** that fuses:
- **GDELT** event-based news signals (near real-time, 15-min updates)
- **EIA** weekly crude oil inventory data
- **Macro-financial indicators** (VIX returns, 10-year Treasury yield)

for weekly binary directional classification (**UP / DOWN**) of WTI crude oil, with a deterministic rule engine encoding economic domain knowledge and a 30-seed robustness evaluation framework.

## Key Results

| Metric | Value |
|---|---|
| F1-score (out-of-sample, 104 weeks) | **0.667** |
| Mean F1 across 30 seeds | 0.630 ± 0.019 |
| Signal-guided cumulative return | **+114.4%** (Sharpe = 1.27) |
| Passive unhedged baseline | +19.2% (Sharpe = 0.41) |
| Seeds beating the passive baseline | 30 / 30 |
| Ensemble (GDELT + technical model) | F1 = 0.678, +125.9% cumulative return |

Test period: May 2024 – April 2026 (104 weeks), characterized by U.S.-China trade escalation and the March 2026 Strait of Hormuz closure.

## Methodology

1. **Monthly baseline model** — XGBoost + Empirical Mode Decomposition (EMD) on macro-financial features; establishes the empirical case for higher-frequency modeling by showing 4 of 8 errors were geopolitical shocks invisible to lagged macro data.
2. **Weekly technical model** — Price/technical/macro features at lag 0–52, serves as a price-history baseline.
3. **GDELT-augmented model** — Adds narrative tone, coverage volume, and causal event signals (supply threats, trade tensions, China demand) with a causal feature engineering pipeline.
4. **Rule engine (A5)** — Deterministic override/boost rules combining GDELT event signals with EIA inventory confirmation.
5. **Macro-financial augmentation** — Adds VIX returns and T10Y yield changes as complementary regime signals (`A5+vix_ret`, `A5+t10y_fall`).
6. **Ensemble** — Combines the GDELT model with the technical model via a targeted DOWN-override rule in specific disagreement conditions.

Validation includes purged cross-validation with a 4-week embargo, label permutation testing, contemporaneous correlation checks, and an intentional-leakage calibration test.

